{{Infobox Politician | image = | | name = Abel LeBlanc | small| caption = | birth_date ={{Birth based on age as of date|79|2014|9|19}} | birth_place = [[Saint John, New Brunswick]] | residence = | office = [[Legislative Assembly of New Brunswick|MLA]] for [[Saint John Lancaster]] | term_start = 2003 | term_end = 2010 | predecessor = [[Norm McFarlane]] | successor = [[Dorothy Shephard]] | party = [[New Brunswick New Democratic Party|New Democratic Party]] | otherparty = [[New Brunswick Liberal Association|Liberal]] ''(until 2014) | religion = | occupation = [[Longshoreman]] }}
'''Abel LeBlanc''' (born c. 1936) is a [[politician]] in the [[province (Canada)|province]] of [[New Brunswick]], Canada. He was elected to the [[Legislative Assembly of New Brunswick]] in [[New Brunswick general election, 2003|2003]].<ref>http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/new-brunswick-votes-2014/abel-leblanc-says-he-s-not-a-new-democrat-in-his-heart-1.2771582</ref>
He represented the [[electoral district]] of [[Saint John Lancaster]] as a Liberal.
LeBlanc was born in [[Saint John, New Brunswick]], the son of Abel LeBlanc and Domitilde Gallant. He joined the [[Canadian Army]] and then went on to work at the Port of Saint John. On February 11, 2010, LeBlanc was expelled from the legislature following a verbal outburst, which included giving two Tory MLAs the finger.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/n-b-mla-expelled-for-rude-gesture-1.925628 "N.B. MLA expelled for rude gesture"]. [[CBC News]], February 11, 2010.</ref>
In June 2014 the [[New Brunswick New Democratic Party]] announced LeBlanc had joined, and that he will run as their candidate in his former riding for that year's provincial [[New Brunswick general election, 2014|election]].<ref name=NDPjoin>{{cite news|title=Ex-Liberal MLA Abel LeBlanc will run for NDP|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/ex-liberal-mla-abel-leblanc-will-run-for-ndp-1.2669385|accessdate=9 June 2014|work=CBC News|date=9 June 2014}}</ref>
